---
import LegalLayout from '../layouts/LegalLayout.astro';
import { SITE } from '../lib/site';
---

<LegalLayout title="Fact-Checking Policy" description="The standards TrailNestCo uses to verify specifications, claims, and pricing before publication." path="/fact-checking-policy" updated="June 1, 2026">
  <p>
    Accuracy is the foundation of {SITE.name}'s credibility. Every published article passes through a
    dedicated fact-checking step before it goes live, separate from the original drafting.
  </p>

  <h2>What we verify</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Specifications</strong> — Dimensions, weight, materials, capacity, and technical claims are checked against the manufacturer's official documentation.</li>
    <li><strong>Pricing &amp; availability</strong> — Listed prices are checked against the linked retailer at time of publication and re-checked on each update cycle.</li>
    <li><strong>Comparative claims</strong> — Any statement comparing one product to another ("lighter than," "more durable than") is checked against a documented source — our own testing notes, manufacturer data, or a cited third-party test.</li>
    <li><strong>Quotes &amp; data</strong> — Any statistic or quote attributed to a study, brand representative, or outside source is linked to its original source where publicly available.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Who checks it</h2>
  <p>
    A senior editor — distinct from the article's original writer — performs the fact-check. For
    camping and outdoor content this is typically <a href="/authors/james-carter">James Carter</a>; for
    home, travel, and EDC content it is typically <a href="/authors/sarah-nguyen">Sarah Nguyen</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Update cadence</h2>
  <p>
    Buying guides and reviews are scheduled for re-verification at minimum once a year, and immediately
    when we're notified a product has been discontinued, recalled, or materially changed. The visible
    "Updated" date on each article reflects the most recent fact-check pass, not just a cosmetic edit.
  </p>

  <h2>Reporting an error</h2>
  <p>
    Readers can flag a suspected inaccuracy at any time by emailing
    <a href={`mailto:${SITE.business.editorialEmail}`}>{SITE.business.editorialEmail}</a> with the article
    URL and the specific claim in question. We aim to investigate and respond within 5 business days.
  </p>
</LegalLayout>
